40|$|Using {{a sample}} of German firms, we {{investigate}} the financial statement effects of adopting International Accounting Standards (IAS) during 1998 through 2002. We find that total assets and <b>book</b> <b>value</b> of equity, as well as variability of <b>book</b> <b>value</b> and income, are significantly higher under IAS than under German GAAP (<b>HGB).</b> In addition, <b>book</b> <b>value</b> and income are no more value relevant under IAS than under HGB, and HGB (IAS) income is highly persistent (transitory). Finally, we find weak evidence that IAS income exhibits greater conditional conservatism than HGB income. Our {{results are consistent with}} the fair-value (income smoothing) orientation of IAS (HGB). © 2007 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC...|$|R
