40|$|Many of the less-developed {{countries}} have required foreign companies to settle nationalization claims on {{a basis of}} <b>book</b> <b>values.</b> These <b>book</b> <b>values</b> are based on generally accepted accounting principles that tend to make <b>book</b> <b>values</b> lower than current far values. As a result, nationalization claims that are settled {{on the basis of}} <b>book</b> <b>values</b> are biased against the owners of the nationalized companies. Accountants should disclose, in notes to the financial statements and in the auditors' reports, that <b>book</b> <b>values</b> do not reflect current fair values, so that it will be evident that the financial statement do not provide an appropriate basis for settling nationalization claims. © 1973 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1973) 4, 15 – 30...|$|R
